lore how social relations, intimacy and trust are built in the online environment and then extended into the offline contexts of actual tourism and travel. Being active couchsurfers themselves, the authors scrutinise the candid claim by much of the online hospitality community that couchsurfing creates a »better world«. The book is key reading for anyone interested in how computer mediated communication is changing contemporary forms of contact, travel and hospitality, and the kinds of cosmopolitism it brings into being.Authors: David Picard, Sonja Buchberger, Jennie Germann Molz, Dennis Zuev, De-Jung Chen, Bernard Schéou, Jun-E Tan, Paula Bialski and Nelson Graburn.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCosmopolitanism. 0aCulture and tourism. 0aHospitality industryxData processing. 0aOnline social networks. 0aTourismxSocial aspects. 0aTourismxTechnological innovations. 4aCosmopolitanism. 4aCultural Studies. 4aGlobalization. 4aHospitality. 4aInternet. 4aOnline Communities. 4aSocial Relations. 4aTourism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aCosmopolitanism.  aCultural Studies.  aGlobalization.  aHospitality.  aInternet.  aOnline Communities.  aSocial Relations.  aTourism.1 aBialski, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchberger, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchberger, Sonja, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChen, De-Jung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGermann Molz, Jennie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraburn, Nelson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPicard, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPicard, D